I find this class confusing to reason about.  Like it's not clear what it represents at any moment and what the valid states are when I look at the code that uses it.  I mean, I can follow what's happening, but it's subtle.

What I meant was something like this:
```
class fft_size
{
public:
    explicit fft_size(long x_dim) : x_(x_dim){}
    /*! 
        ensures
            - x() == x_dim
            - y() == 1
    !*/
    fft_size(long x_dim, long y_dim) : x_(x_dim), y_(y_dim) {}
    /*! 
        ensures
            - x() == x_dim
            - y() == y_dim
    !*/

    // get size of dimensions.
    long x() const { return x_; }
    long y() const { return y_; }

    long num_elements() const { return x_*y_; }

    bool operator==(const fft_size& other) const;
    uint32 hash() const;
private:
    
    long x_ = 1;
    long y_ = 1;
};
```

That object is really simple and immutable.  It always represents the same thing.  There isn't optionality about being 1D sometimes and 2D other times.  A 1D FFT just means y==1.  If 3D ffts are needed later someone can add a z (and even a w) dimension.

You could add global helper functions for the higher level stuff you are doing with it.  For example, you might say ```
if (is_1d(some_fft_size))
    // do whatever
```
and that would make the code that uses it more readable.

