What do you both think about renaming the `awkward_*` functions to include "cpu" in the name: `awkwardcpu_*`? Symmetry is good, but the "c" vs "g" could get lost when looking at them casually; at least the asymmetry makes it easy to distinguish them from a distance (without glasses). Separating the "cpu" vs "gpu" from the "awkward" with an underscore could help with that as well: `awkward_cpu_*` vs `awkward_gpu_*` are more easily distinguishable.

The primary purpose of this tag is to avoid symbol conflicts. Since the functions are compiled as `extern "C"`, there's nothing that keeps one library's symbols from clashing with another library's symbols except the name. Beyond the fact that the `Kernel` class (or `kernel` namespace) centralizes dispatch between CPU and GPU, it also allows us to remove this prefix, since it's now isolated.

